ce:section.ce:para:
To further investigate the effect of nitric acid addition on the fluorescence properties of LCDs, the three-dimensional (3D) fluorescence spectra of LCDs were plotted (Fig. 7
                        ), and the optimal excitation and emission wavelengths and QY of LCDs were summarized in Table 2
                        . With the increase of nitric acid addition, the optimal excitation wavelength of the LCDs blueshifted from 394 nm to 377 nm, and the optimal emission wavelength blueshifted from 517 nm to 499 nm. This blue-shifted behavior of the excitation and emission centers may be influenced by two aspects. On the one hand, the particular emission blue-shift behavior may be related to quantum domain-limited effects. The particle size of LCDs becomes smaller under a strongly acidic environment, the π-electron leaving domain is restricted, and the band gap increases and exhibits the emission wavelength blueshift (Sk et al., 2014). On the other hand, HNO3 also introduces C-N in LCDs, and the formation of pyridine and pyrrole structures can induce blue-shifted emission behavior (Zhu, L. et al., 2021). In addition, the nitric acid addition enhancement also increased the QY of LCDs from 2.61% (LCDs-0) to 10.17% (LCDs-2.4). The increase in QY can be explained by the synergistic effect of the carbon core and surface states. The strong acidic environment increased the degree of graphitization and endowed the LCDs with a more complete sp2 carbon core and enhanced intrinsic fluorescence (Chen et al., 2022). In addition, the doping of N forms electron-donating structures such as pyrroles in LCDs. It increases the electron cloud density in the sp2 conjugated π-domain and reduces the non-radiative complexation of LCDs, ultimately increasing the QY by a factor of ∼3.9.
